[1] Diarrhea - Bangladesh
Date: Sat 24 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmaill.org>
Source: New Nation on line [edited]
<http://nation.ittefaq.com/artman/publish/article_11000.shtml>

Central Bangladesh braces for deluge - diarrhea attacks 50 000
-----------------------------------------------
Continuing floods, which have already created havoc in 2/3 of the districts
of the country, are fast approaching the capital of Dhaka, placing millions
of people, without the prospect of adequate relief, at risk for outbreaks
of water-borne disease.
The Health Directorate Control Room said that waterborne diseases, like
diarrhea, had broken out in the flood-affected areas, including Comilla,
Gaibandha, Pabna, Narayanganj, Tangail, Brahmanbaria, Barisal, Sunamganj,
Sylhet, Jamalpur, Netrokona, Habiganj, Moulvibazar, and Dhaka. The bulletin
of the control room said that some 3000 people were struck by diarrhea
during last 48 hours. But, unofficial sources reported that the number of
diarrhea patients in the affected areas stood at 50 000 by Fri 23 Jul 2004.
Our correspondents from different affected areas add that water-borne
diseases have been spreading in an epidemic form, while the victims are
facing acute shortages of oral saline, water purification tablets, and
proper medical services.
--
