[2] Diarrhea & Cholera - Philippines (Pangasinan) (03)
Date: Tue 20 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedamil.org>
Source: Manila Bulletin [edited]
<http://www.mb.com.ph/PROV2004072014422.html>

The World Health Organization (WHO) is willing to help the Philippines
address the problem posed by cholera, particularly in Pangasinan, where 81
cases of vibrio cholera were found from among the 2055 patients afflicted
with acute gastroenteritis.
This information was conveyed by a team of medical experts sent to Dagupan
last Thu 15 Jul 2004, by Health Secretary Manuel Dayrit, to assess the
situation, and, the operation of Department of Health (DoH) personnel in
the field against cholera.
Dagupan City has become the DoH regional office's center for operations in
the fight against cholera, which, records show, is still raging in 38 of
the 48 towns and cities of Pangasinan.
DoH Regional Director Eduardo Janairo said his staff, including sanitary
engineers, has submitted, to the DoH team, a "wish list" of equipment and
facilities they would like the WHO to deliver to Pangasinan to boost the
efforts toward stopping the cholera outbreak.
The WHO has placed the Philippines under its cholera "watch list," after it
required DoH to report the cases of cholera that it encountered.
Janairo said this wish list would be a big boost in the fight against
cholera, because the DoH lacks logistics, such as chlorine testing kits,
equipment to identify the potability of water, chlorine, and others
materials which the local government units may not be able to buy.
--
