[7] Cholera - Cameroon
Date: 25 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Panapress, 19 Jul 2004 [in Portuguese, summarized by Mod.JW, edited]
<http://www.panapress.com>

Around 128 people have died, out of 6377 affected by cholera, since the
beginning of 2004, according to the Ministry of Public Health. The most
affected provinces are the coastal, west, southwest, extreme north, south,
and central. The capital, Yaounde, is now infected, with 21 cases reported
in 2 weeks. [Compare 26 deaths out of 2048 cases reported to WHO as of 20
May 2004. See Cholera, diarrhea & dysentery update 2004 (14) 20040628.1726.
- Mod.JW]
The causes most quoted are poor water quality and a lack of attention to
the rules of hygiene. An average of only 7 out of 10 families nationwide
have access to potable water, and, only 44 percent of families do in
Yaounde, according to the national water authority.
--
