[8] Cholera - Austria ex India
Date: Thu 22 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Eurosurveillance [edited]
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ew/2004/040722.asp>

2 cases of imported cholera from India in Austrian travelers
----------------------------------------------
2 confirmed cholera cases (_Vibrio cholerae_ 01, subserotype Inaba, biotype
El Tor) were reported to the Austrian ministry of health by the Vienna
Regional Health Board, and the national cholera reference laboratory in
Vienna, on 2 Jun 2004. Both cases were in 58-year-old Austrian men who
admitted themselves to the Allgemeines Krankenhaus Wien (Vienna General
Hospital) directly after arrival at Vienna International Airport on 26 May
2004, because they were suffering from diarrhea.
Patient 1 had become ill on 20 May 2004, and, received intravenous
re-hydration in the outpatient department of the Medical University of
Vienna's Division of Infectious Diseases, starting on 27 May 2004, because
of the severity of his illness. Patient 2 fell ill on 23 May 2004, but, was
not severely ill, and left Vienna to take another holiday in the Austrian
region of Styria on 28 May 2004.
Stool samples were taken from both patients, and routinely investigated for
_V. cholerae_ (culture). On 2 Jun 2004, when the diagnosis was confirmed,
patient 1 was kept in hospital isolation, and hygiene control measures were
reinforced. Patient 2 was kept in private isolation at his hotel in
Grobming, Styria, and, was visited daily by the district public health
officer. After 2 negative stool samples from each patient, they were both
released from isolation. Stool samples were taken twice from each family
member, and all tested negative.
The travel history revealed that the 2 friends had traveled to India on 24
Apr 2004 for a private trekking tour, where they were accompanied by 3
Indian Sherpa guides and an Indian cook. The travel route included Uttar
Pradesh, Hardwar, Rishikesh, and Kedarnath, and a boat trip on the Ganges.
The travelers had not been vaccinated against cholera but used the usual
preventive measures for travelers, such as water disinfection and hand washing.
They both traveled back from New Delhi to Vienna on a direct Austrian
Airlines flight on 27 May 2004. Investigations revealed that approximately
230 passengers were booked on the flight, most of whom were Indian citizens
taking connecting flights to London, New York, and Paris. A passenger list
could not be provided, because the check-in at Delhi was administered by
Indian Airlines. Attempts by Austrian Airlines to obtain the list were
unsuccessful, and so, no identification of passengers, who continued their
journey beyond Vienna, was possible.
However, only a minor infection risk for the co-travelers existed: the
patients were seated in economy class on the lower deck, and no other
passengers were seated in the same row of seats. After using the lavatory
in economy class, both patients reported careful hand washing with soap and
water. Additionally, no contact with other people, such as handshaking, was
reported, and no medical help was required. According to Austrian Airlines,
no crew members reported having diarrhea.
In accordance with Decision 2119/98, the Austrian ministry of health
immediately informed other European Union member states about the cholera
cases via the Early Warning and Response System. In accordance with
International Health Regulations, the World Health Organization Regional
Office for Europe was also informed.
[By: Reinhild Strauss, Jana Stirling, Christine Bruns, Manfred Hausmann,
Gunther Wewalka, Florian Thalhammer, and Hubert Hrabcik]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
